__data__.text: american revolution: the american revolution was an ideological and political movement in the thirteen colonies that led to the american revolutionary war and the establishment of the united states of america

thirteen colonies: settlers  fur traders  and land speculators in the thirteen colonies were affected by the royal proclamation of 1763<SEP>the thirteen colonies were the british colonies in north america that played a significant role in the american revolution
british america: british america refers to the territories in north america under british rule during the american revolution
american revolutionary war: the american revolutionary war was a conflict between the thirteen colonies and great britain  resulting in the colonies  independence
battles of lexington and concord: the battles of lexington and concord marked the beginning of the american revolutionary war on april 19  1775
leaders of the american revolution: leaders of the american revolution were colonial separatist leaders who advocated for independence from great britain

second continental congress: the second continental congress represented the colonies and played a crucial role in the american revolution  appointing george washington and adopting the declaration of independence
independence hall: independence hall in philadelphia was the location where the second continental congress convened and adopted the declaration of independence
continental army: the continental army was formed by the second continental congress and led by george washington during the american revolutionary war
george washington: george washington was appointed as the commander in chief of the continental army and played a pivotal role in the american revolution
declaration of independence: the declaration of independence was adopted by the second continental congress in 1776  declaring the colonies  independence from great britain
siege of yorktown: the siege of yorktown in 1781 was a decisive victory for the continental army led by george washington  leading to the end of the revolutionary war
king george iii: king george iii of great britain played a significant role in the events leading to the american revolution and the eventual recognition of american independence
treaty of paris: the treaty of paris in 1783 formally ended the american revolutionary war and recognized the independence of the united states of america
stamp act congress: the stamp act congress in 1765 protested against taxation without representation  a key issue that fueled the american revolution
boston massacre: the boston massacre in 1770 was a violent confrontation between colonists and british troops  escalating tensions in the lead up to the revolution
boston tea party: the boston tea party in 1773 was a protest against british taxation policies  symbolizing colonial resistance to british rule
sons of liberty: the sons of liberty were activists who played a role in events like the boston tea party  advocating for colonial rights
first continental congress: the first continental congress in 1774 marked the colonies  united response to british policies  laying the groundwork for the revolution
carpenters  hall: carpenters  hall in philadelphia was the venue for the first continental congress  where colonial delegates gathered to address grievances
articles of confederation: the articles of confederation were debated by the second continental congress as an early attempt at establishing a governing framework for the colonies
thomas jefferson: thomas jefferson was a key figure in drafting the declaration of independence  embodying revolutionary ideals of liberty and equality
marquis de lafayette: marquis de lafayette  a french military officer  supported the american cause during the revolutionary war  aiding in the victory at yorktown

french and indian war: the french and indian war  ending in 1763  marked a turning point in british colonial policies and set the stage for tensions leading to the american revolution<SEP>the french and indian war involved british regulars  colonial volunteers  and colonial spending  leading to territorial changes<SEP>the french and indian war occurred between 1754 1763 involving british and colonial forces against france

capt  levi preston: capt  levi preston  a colonist from danvers  massachusetts  expressed the sentiment of self governance and autonomy that fueled the american rebellion against england<SEP>capt  levi preston  a colonist from danvers  massachusetts  expressed the sentiment of self governance and rebellion against england
british parliament: british parliament imposed taxes and policies on the colonies  leading to grievances and resistance that culminated in the american revolution

royal proclamation of 1763: the proclamation designated territory between the appalachian mountains and the mississippi river as an indian reserve<SEP>the royal proclamation of 1763 defined territorial boundaries and policies in north america after the french and indian war  impacting colonial relations with britain

salutary neglect: salutary neglect was a british policy of non interference in colonial affairs that shifted after the french and indian war  contributing to colonial discontent and calls for autonomy
colonial rule: colonial rule refers to the governance and policies imposed by britain on the thirteen colonies  leading to tensions and resistance that sparked the american revolution
thirteen colonies  autonomy: the thirteen colonies sought greater autonomy from britain after years of self governance and independence in managing their affairs
charles ii: charles ii  the king during the stuart restoration  faced resistance from massachusetts and the new england colonies
james ii: james ii  brother of charles ii  attempted to bring new england under direct english control  leading to colonial opposition
edmund andros: edmund andros was appointed royal governor and played a significant role in governing the dominion of new england
william and mary: william and mary  the new monarchs after the glorious revolution  granted new charters to the new england colonies
colonial assemblies: colonial assemblies played a crucial role in the self government and restoration of rights in new england after the glorious revolution
town meetings: town meetings were restricted during dominion rule but regained importance in local democratic self government
house of lords: the house of lords represented aristocrats in the british empire s constitutional monarchy
house of commons: the house of commons was controlled by the gentry and merchants and played a key role in governing with the king
british subjects: british subjects on both sides of the atlantic claimed the unwritten british constitution  emphasizing personal liberty and rights
royal governor: the royal governor was appointed by the crown to exercise executive power in the colonies
colonial militias: colonial militias defended the colonies and played a crucial role in self governance before the american revolution
robert middlekauff: historian robert middlekauff highlighted the self governing nature of americans before the american revolution
british government: the british government fielded soldiers and contributed to the war effort during the french and indian war
colonies: the colonies contributed money to the war effort during the french and indian war
great britain: great britain defeated france during the french and indian war and acquired territory east of the mississippi river
bute ministry: the bute ministry decided to garrison soldiers in north america in 1763
british army officers: approximately 1 500 politically well connected british army officers were allowed to remain on active duty with full pay in north america in 1763
native americans: native americans were involved in conflicts with white colonists and british soldiers in newly acquired territories
french: the french were defeated by great britain during the french and indian war
spanish: the spanish were present in florida during the french and indian war
white colonists: white colonists instigated conflicts with native americans in the west during the french and indian war
customs duties: british soldiers helped collect customs duties in the newly acquired territories
migration: migration increased beyond the appalachian mountains after the french threat was removed
pontiac s war: native americans launched pontiac s war in response to westward migration and british presence
grenville ministry: the grenville ministry issued the royal proclamation of 1763  affecting westward migration and indian territories
45 000 soldiers: 45 000 soldiers were fielded during the french and indian war  half of which were british regulars
colonial volunteers: colonial volunteers made up half of the 45 000 soldiers fielded during the french and indian war
money contribution: the colonies contributed money to the war effort during the french and indian war
reimbursement: two fifths of the spending by the colonies during the french and indian war was reimbursed by the british government
north america: north america was the location where the bute ministry decided to garrison soldiers in 1763
standing army: a standing army was stationed in north america in 1763 to provide defense and prevent conflicts
westward migration: migration beyond the appalachian mountains increased after the french threat was removed  leading to conflicts
indian reserve: the territory between the appalachian mountains and the mississippi river was designated as an indian reserve in 1763
french revolution: the french revolution was a period of political and societal change in france  marked by significant events such as the estates general of 1789 and the coup of 18 brumaire in 1799

estates general: the estates general is proposed as the body to approve new taxes  facing challenges due to historical precedents and representation issues<SEP>the estates general is proposed as the body to approve new taxes  last meeting in 1614<SEP>the estates general of 1789 was a crucial event that marked the beginning of the french revolution  leading to the formation of the national assembly
coup of 18 brumaire: the coup of 18 brumaire on 9 november 1799 marked the end of the french revolution and the establishment of the consulate under napoleon bonaparte
ancien r gime: the ancien r gime refers to the old regime in france  characterized by social  political  and economic factors that contributed to the revolution
louis xvi: louis xvi was the king of france during the french revolution  whose attempted flight to varennes and subsequent execution were significant events
national assembly: the national assembly was formed by the representatives of the third estate during the french revolution  leading to radical measures and reforms
storming of the bastille: the storming of the bastille on 14 july was a pivotal event in the french revolution  symbolizing the people s uprising against the monarchy
reign of terror: the reign of terror was a period of mass executions and political repression during the french revolution  led by the radical jacobins
estates general of 1789: the estates general of 1789 was a crucial event that marked the beginning of the french revolution  leading to the formation of the national assembly

__data__.text: crisis of the ancien r gime: the crisis of the ancien r gime refers to the social  economic  and political challenges faced by the pre revolutionary french state
revolutionary tribunal: the revolutionary tribunal was responsible for trying and sentencing individuals during the reign of terror in the french revolution
thermidorian reaction: the thermidorian reaction marked the end of the reign of terror and the radical phase of the french revolution  leading to a more moderate government
committee of public safety: the committee of public safety was a governing body during the french revolution  known for its role in the reign of terror and radical policies
directory: the directory was the governing body of france following the reign of terror  characterized by instability and eventually overthrown in the coup of 18 brumaire
consulate: the consulate was established after the coup of 18 brumaire  with napoleon bonaparte as first consul  marking a new phase in french governance
tax farmers: tax farmers are contracted to collect taxes  keeping a portion as personal profit
nobility: nobility benefits from exemptions  leading to a tax burden mainly on peasants
church: church benefits from exemptions  influencing the distribution of the tax burden
peasants: peasants bear the main tax burden due to exemptions enjoyed by the nobility and church
reform: reform is difficult due to the need to register new tax laws with regional bodies that can block them
anglo french war of 1778 1783: the anglo french war of 1778 1783 was primarily funded by france through loans
monarchy: the monarchy borrows heavily post war  leading to a debt crisis and high debt servicing requirements
calonne: calonne proposes tax reforms and faces rejection by nobility dominated assemblies
brienne: brienne submits new taxes for approval  facing rejection by the parlements
crown: the crown faces a political crisis with the parlements over tax reforms
parlements: the parlements defend ancient rights against proposed tax reforms  leading to a national crisis
public opinion: public opinion supports the parlements in the conflict with the crown over tax reforms
riots: riots break out in several towns in support of the parlements during the crisis
jacques necker: jacques necker replaces brienne as the finance minister during the crisis
parlement of paris: the parlement of paris rules on the format of the estates general meeting  favoring the clergy and nobility
society of thirty: the society of thirty campaigns for increased representation and individual voting rights
abb  siey s: abb  siey s issues influential pamphlets advocating for the third estate s representation and rights
jean joseph mounier: jean joseph mounier organizes regional support for increased representation and voting rights
antoine barnave: antoine barnave supports demands for increased representation and individual voting
maximilien robespierre: maximilien robespierre advocates for increased representation and individual voting rights
taxes: taxes are collected but not proportionally reflected in the economy  leading to issues with tax farmers and exemptions benefiting the nobility and church
debt crisis: the monarchy faces a debt crisis due to heavy borrowing post war  impacting state revenue and financial stability
assembly of notables: the assembly of notables rejects new taxes proposed by calonne  leading to further financial challenges
crisis: the conflict between the crown and the parlements escalates into a national crisis  shaping political discourse and actions
political clubs: the relaxation of laws against political clubs allows for increased political activism and debate
political pamphlets: the publication of political pamphlets becomes a significant form of expression and debate during the crisis
